      <profileDesc>
         <abstract>
            <p> The work referred to as ‘gadl’ of ʾAlāniqos is currently attested uniquely in <ref
                  type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/ANLcr23">Rome, Biblioteca
               dell’Accademia Nazionale dei Lincei, Conti Rossini 23</ref>, where it consists of a
               chronology of Ethiopian kings, twelve miracles, a malkǝʾ-hymn to Taṭamqa Madḫǝn, a
               disciple of ʾAlāniqos, and a spiritual genealogy of Ethiopian monks. It does not
               contain a vita proper (see <bibl
                  corresp="http://zotero.org/groups/358366/items/BWJEWURQ">
                  <seg type="journalArticle"><!-- attributes from original bibl-->
                  </seg>
                  <ptr target="bm:Marrassini1982Alaniqos" />
                  <title level="a">Il &lt;hi rend="italics"&gt;Gadla Alāniqos&lt;/hi&gt;</title>
                  <title level="j">Egitto e Vicino Oriente</title>
                  <author>
                     <t:forename xmlns:t="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Paolo</t:forename>
                     <t:surname xmlns:t="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Marrassini</t:surname>
                  </author>
                  <date>1982</date>
                  <biblScope unit="volume">5</biblScope>
                  <biblScope unit="page">143-182</biblScope>
               </bibl>). </p>
         </abstract>
